segments.text: first of all mr allen would you tell us something about your early life including the names of your parents the dates of their birth and death the places where they were born where you were born and the the date of your birth and the schools you attended before texas a m okay well my father named charlie allen my mother's name dolly allen my father was born
October 12, 1868, near Smithville, Tennessee.
My mother was born March 11, 1867, and I might just say that she lived to be 102 in two days before she died.
She was born near Atlanta, Georgia, and moved to Texas with her family in 1874.
Did she ever tell you anything about that trip?
Well, not very much.
She was about seven years old when they made that trip.
And of course, you know, back in those days, we youngsters didn't ask the parents too much or grandparents too much about the experiences.
Quite a family of them came at the same time, and I believe they came on the train to some central point, and then they had relatives near central Texas, near McGregor, Texas, where they settled.
Uh-huh.
When did your father come to Texas?

Well, he came to Texas about 1890, and he had a brother came out ahead of him down near McGregor, Texas, and settled there, and my father came there and worked several years, and then my mother was married in 1895, and he bought several farms there, and he died in May the 21st, 1954.
My mother died, I might say, March the 13th, 1971.
And you were born in McGregor, then?
I was born in McGregor, Texas, on March the 27th, 1898.
Did you go to the schools in McGregor?
Well, yes, but before that I went to a country school.
It was named Hawthorne.
We lived to the miles from the school.
It was kind of sparse in those days, and the wolves were around and that kind of thing.
My parents wouldn't let me go to school when I was eight years old, but I started in the second grade.
You know, about the only thing we had in those days was old readers.
And then I went there for five, six years, then went to McGregor School and graduated from high school there.
Was that a one-room school?
Yes, one-room school, country school.
Big old coal-burning stove, one teacher, 30 or 40 boys and girls, country boys and girls.
And then you went, what, through the eighth grade there, and then high school in McGregor?
Well, I went about seventh grade there, then went to McGregor, and went through high school, McGregor, and then I enrolled down at the Aggies.
What factors were involved in your choice of A&M?
Well, I had some schoolmates go there year two ahead of me, and the stories they told, it was fascinating.
I couldn't resist.
I had no second thoughts.
Did, uh, did you go through any particular special procedures to be admitted to A&M?

Well, as I recall, we sent our, the principal of our high school sent the transcripts and we made them application and, um, I still have the copy of that transcript and, by the way, I have all my, um, report cards, even when high school and college station, A&M.
Uh-huh.
But there wasn't much getting in then if you,
You know, it'd get by and your dad could pay for it, but that was it.
So you had a diploma then from?
McGregor High School.
McGregor High School.
Yes, sir.
And that was an acceptable school for A&M, so.
Yes.
Were there any, say, advanced placement tests?
Now, today a student coming to A&M can take a test and, say, get credit for freshman English or one semester of it.
Could you do anything like that?
Well, we never offered anything like that.
We never had anything that presented or, no.
Since you were somewhat familiar with the customs of the school, your reaction might be different than others, but what was your first reaction to A&M and College Station when you got there?
Well, I thought this was the grandest place in the world.
I'm assuming you went there by train?
Oh yeah, sure, and they'd pile up those trunks that were mountain-sized.
Everybody had a trunk in those days.
And they hauled them to your room, wherever you were assigned.
then the school was expecting you and they had a room assigned to you.
How did you know where to go when you got to the school?
Gosh, it's been so far back.
You know, I think they had down at the depots, they had guides and things like that to kind of...
lead you around and get you associated and kind of place you.
I had no particular idea of where I'd be placed and what military company or dormitory when I arrived there.
But I believe that's the way it was.
They had kind of guides.
How did you get your trunk from the train station up to campus?
Well, there's an old man there with a kind of a
like the old grocery cart years and years ago, wagons had a couple of mules and he'd load those things on that truck or wagon and haul them to his room.
He had two, three helpers, colored boys, and they'd take them up to your room.
I presume you had your name printed on the outside of yours or?
Well, I suppose I did, but we probably put a tag on them and room number and dormitory number.
Okay.
Could you describe for us a typical day

during your years at A&M, that is, the time and procedures for getting up and about going to meals, the time you spent in class and what you did other than classwork, and then the time and procedure of going to bed.
Well, soon after we arrived that few days, two or three days, we were enrolled and
sign the course that we're going to take, sign up for that, and they would give us, sign us to a military company, and a dormitory, and a room number.
Of course, a couple of my friends went down with me from McGregor, and we roomed together.
Otherwise, we'd have drawn or selected roommates, and of course, about the meals, the first day or two, of course, we'd just hear them, scare them, get the mess all the best way we could.
But as soon as they were organized,
You know, we lined up on that military walk and we marched to all the meals, breakfast and the loon and dinner time.

And then after the meal, of course, we left the meal, the rest hall, and dispersed without military formation back to our dormitory to get ready to go to class or if we didn't have any classes to, you know, other activities.
Now that would prevail all the four years I was there.
And of course, by going to bed, we had done
confined to quarters soon after dark, a study period for about a couple, three hours.
And in the early years there, we had a sentinel that marched up and down the halls with a bayonet and carrying a rifle.
And to see that no one left the rooms or gathered in rooms for bull sessions and that kind of thing.
And then about 9.45, something like that, they had a bugle blow that released us from the study and gave us about 15 minutes to get in bed.
And they came around and checked the doors to see that you were there.
But in the later years, they kind of eased up on that slightly, somewhat.
But they had very close supervision over the boys being in the room and not having bull sessions and that kind of thing.
Well, when was your room inspected?

Well, of course, the company commander came around quite frequently to inspect the rooms, to see they were orderly, the beds were made, and they're clean, and the clothes are in the closet, and that kind of thing.
And occasionally, the head military men from the United States, you know, were signed up for the ROTC units, came around on a general inspection.
and they would have our closet doors open and everything to have them inspect in the closets and under the bed and everything else.
Were you given notice that this inspection was to occur?
Yeah, the general inspection, yes, usually yes.

But the company commander's inspection was sort of... Well, he could come around anytime and, you know, he might, well, on the floor there, sometimes some of the boys might get unruly and noise and that kind of thing, and, you know, you know how boys are.
Yeah, and I lived in a dormitory for four years.
What was life like in the dormitory?
I know that you said there was a time, a quiet period, when you had to be in your room studying, but during the rest of the day,

Well, of course, if you weren't in class, you probably went to your room and prepared for other class sessions or maybe lay down and take a nap or maybe clean your rifle or shine your shoes or get your laundry ready or write a letter back home.
You know, you always need a little money, you know.
You kept your rifle in your room then?
Oh, yes, sir.
Did you have live ammunition or...
Well, when we'd go out on rifle range practice, but not in the dormitory.
Not in the dormitory.
No, but we'd go out to rifle practice.
We did, yes.
Okay.
Just kind of an aside, I know that at one period, one of the favorite things was shooting out what's called Prexy's Moon.
Oh, yeah.
Yeah.
Of course, some of those boys, you know, sometimes, you know, it's easy to get a hold of a shell, you know.
You know how boys are.
They pick up things, and they shoot out Dr. W. Brazell was the president in those days.
Uh-huh.
And, oh, he was a dandy fella, parted his hair in the middle.
He was a wonderful fella.
He taught a Sunday school class there, too.
Uh-huh.
Well, I'd understood that he did that for a goodly number of years.
Yes, he did.
Oh, they'd shoot that precious moon out.
Could you tell me what dormitories you lived in?
Well, at first I lived in Ross Hall.
And that was right on the military walk facing west, one of the old time halls there.
Been gone a long, long time.
And he called his students there the Ross Hall Hellraisers.
That's what they were.
Was that just when you were there, or?
Well, no, that was been going on for years.
Rawls Hall had a reputation.
And I lived there, and then I lived in Mitchell Hall.
That was a new one at that time, just north of the YMCA.
That's gone now.
Then I lived in Leggett Hall, and...
And Mitchell was torn down, I believe, two years ago.
Something like that.
Leggett, I believe, is still standing.
Yeah, still uses it.
And I lived in Ross again.
I lived in Ross, too.
And, of course, in that day, the toilet facilities in Ross, see, it was three-story buildings, I recall.
The toilet facilities were on the third floor.
I believe the third floor.
Second or third, I can't remember which, but you had to go up there.
Okay.
I might say the bugle stand, you know, they blew the bugle, you know, for all formations and classes.
The stand at that time was a great big horn, and it was right out of Ross Hall, but you couldn't miss the...
So you didn't have any problem hearing it?
No, I didn't have any problem hearing it.
Did...
Then you lived in a different dormitory every year you were there.
Well, Ross first in last year.
Well, no, I lived in Mitchell the last year.
I lived in Mitchell two different times, and Ross two different times, and Leggett Hall.
And that's about all the halls I moved in.
But let's see, the newer ones, Mitchell and Leggett, probably had bathrooms on each floor.
Oh, yes, that's right, they did.
And Bazell Hall at that time was the newest.
It was built while I was at Bazell Hall, after Dr. Bazell.
Yeah.
What was the food like in the missile?
Well, of course, we complained about it, but it was real good.
You know, the old, old fellow named Spieser, whom the hall was named for, he was alive in those days.
He was an old Mexican man, as I recall.
And we had wonderful food.
We complained about it a lot, but then it was good substantial.
Boy, I went there with about 125, and I left there with 165, so...
In four years, considering all of the exercise you got, I presume that was it.
Pretty substantial increase.
In those days, we had long tables, about 12, 15 sets of tables.
The upperclassmen at the end, at the corner of the end, the freshmen in here.
And the dessert we called kush in those days.
And every now and then, the upperclassmen say, freshmen, I'm taking your kush today.
That means the freshmen got no dessert.
That happened quite frequently.
Today there's a custom that it's a form of hazing, I guess.
The upperclassman asks the freshman a question, and it's a question if the freshman doesn't find out the answer by a certain time, he has to give up his kush for the day.
Well, we had all kind of trick questions, too, and you never knew what kind of answer that brought on kush.
In those days, we had real hazing now.
We had these belts about that wide.
Mm-hmm.
A lot of little boys, not freshmen, after their day or two, they didn't sit down very frequently.
They got to be a sophomore.
But, you know, it was your friends that hazed you.
It was your friends that hazed you.
That's right.
I imagine, like anything, there were a few who abused it.
Well, maybe a little bit, not much.
You've got a lot of strapping, but it's all good nature.
The freshmen, I might say this,
that would not let them haze them were never very popular.
They were never very popular as a rule.
Oh, at the time, shoot, what's the difference?
It's all over now.
Well, it only lasted for one year anyway.
Only one year.
And then next year, we could do the same thing.
Yeah, yeah.
Pass it on.
Pass it on.
Pass it on, yeah.
Okay.
What privileges did the upperclassmen enjoy that freshmen didn't have?
Well...
Of course, as I say, they got to eat at the end of the table in the corner, and that's where the food was placed when it came in.
That was one thing, and they got the first serving of the food, of course, always.
And, oh, you know, we had to shine their shoes for them and that kind of thing.
That was a privilege not to have to shine your shoes.
Clean the rifle.
They had to do a good job.
And they were granted more permits than that time going to Brine.
You know, in that day and time, we rode that old trolley car.
There were no automobiles in those days, speak of.
And that was quite a thing to go with Brian, go to those picture shows, you know, and that kind of thing, to get away from the reservation.
How often could you go as a freshman?
Well, it seemed like I think we'd go every Saturday afternoon without a permit from, say, after dismissal at noon until formation in the evening, 5, 6 o'clock.
And then, of course, you'd go on special occasions maybe once a month, you know, socially with a permit.
I have some of those old permits here that was granted me.
The permit came from who?
Commandant.
Commandant.
Commandant.
Yeah, commandant.
Military commandant.
And did you have to, did you ask him directly or did you have to go through your company commander?
I went to the company commander.
I think the company commander had to okay it, then it had to be okayed.
But the upperclassmen can go more frequently.
Oh, yes.
And then, of course, in the senior, and I got to be a senior, well, you'd go on.
or without a permit, you know, on Saturday or Sunday, that kind of thing.
Quite frequent here.
What else for you?
Today's students, many of them go home every weekend.
Even, you know, I would imagine at the time when you were there, say, somebody who would have lived in Houston could have gone by train without too much difficulty.
Were any of the students go home on weekends?
Not very often now.
McGregor's got 125 miles from College Station.
I only went home three times in the whole four years, you know.
Well was that a study and you know the military and your studies.
Of course I took electrical engineering which was a lot of math and that kind of thing.
It required a lot of study and we didn't have transportation those days.
No automobiles at all.
Maybe one or two or three.
So mostly you'd go home at Christmas then?
Oh you'd go home Christmas.
Of course I'd get several days off and
And of course we'd always, in those days they had the Cotton Palace Waco, which was kind of like Fair Dallas, only smaller.
We'd go up there and they'd play Baylor every year.
The cadet corps would go up there and stack arms.
And of course I'd go on out and visit my folks overnight while I was there.
And then things like that.
What did, besides going into Baylor,
to Bryan, say, to the movie or anything like that, what other things did the students do for recreation or entertainment?
Well, of course, we were engaged in company athletics in those days.
We had company football teams and old basketball teams and all kinds of things like that.
And, you know, being in a military school like that with classes and supervised quarters, we didn't have a whole lot of time, idle time on your hands.
No.
Well, you didn't have a memorial student center like they have today.
No, no, no.
With pool tables and things of that nature.
Oh, no, no, no.
But were there things that you could do at the YMCA?
Oh, yes, there was things like that.
But, you know, the YMCA in those days was rather small, and they had reading rooms and a few things like that.
And, of course, old boy Casey had a confectionary down the basement there, and you'd go over and get your drinks and all that kind of thing.
You know, it just couldn't accommodate nearly what it should have been, of course.
Because in those days, that was kind of a new thing, you know.
What about in the rooms, did the fellows gather for bull sessions occasionally?

Oh yes, you say when you weren't having class, maybe several of them not having class, they'd gather there for a bull session and all that kind of thing and talk over things and maybe study or and then you know there's games they played you know, you know what games?
Snake eyes and those kind of things, you know.
Uh-huh.
Somebody told me yesterday there was one fellow that he knew that worked his way through school with his pair of dice.
I wouldn't be surprised.
Like Harold Dunn worked his way through the hamburger stand.
Yeah, yeah.
You talked to Harold Dunn, didn't you?
I talked to Harold Dunn, yeah.
He told me about his hamburger stand.
Oh, yeah.
I gather from what he told me that that hamburger stand probably was not in existence when you were there.
No, no.
No, they were not.
We didn't have anything like that.
We didn't eat much between meals.
It wasn't an occasion for it.
They gave us plenty of food, and it was good food.
We complained about it, but it was good food.
And those days, most of the students, you know, a lot of farm boys, they didn't have much money to spend on things like that, you know.
Did you have any favorite instructors when you were there?
Oh yes, Dr. F.C.
Bolton, who was head of the electrical engineering department.
Of course, since I took electrical engineering, he was a great, great fellow.
Very soft-spoken, easy-going, but he was a wonderful, wonderful fellow.
And he gave you a fair deal and that kind of thing.
And then in calculus, they called him Cokie, Cokie Smith.
And they called him Cokie because he, well, some of the boys thought he was slow and kind of sleepy, that kind of thing.
They called him Cokie.
Well, in calculus, we had a line up of alphabetic.
Of course, my name began with A.
And it didn't take me long to find out that Cokie asked me the first question right down the line in calculus.
But it didn't take me long to know that, Jerem, you better get that first problem.
And my mother came down on my graduation and didn't have motels then, you know.
So I got a room to stay that night, too, Cokie Smith.
He told my mother, he said, you know, I was the best calculus student he ever had.
You were always prepared for that first question.
I was prepared.
And you know, if you made a certain grade, you didn't have to take the final examination.
Well, in the assignment, the problems were all pretty much alike, you know, for the assignment, so I don't really have to take any of that.
You say if you had a certain grade, you didn't have to make finals.
Yeah.
Was that for all four years?
I think it is today.
I don't recall, just to tell the truth about it, I don't recall.
You know, I've been out of that 54 years.
Yes, I know.
Today, I think there are no final exams for seniors at all.
Well, it wasn't then, I'm sure, if you didn't make top-level grades or something like that.
And I think if you have a certain grade, then you can be excused from the final.
Yeah.
But if you think you can raise your grade, well, you can go ahead and take the final, and you kind of gamble whether you're going to raise it or lower it.
Of course, there's other professors, you know, and I liked them all.
But, you know, after 54 years, your memory's kind of dull, but I do remember those two very distinctly.
Well, let's see, I believe Mr. Bolton then became dean of engineering.
Yes, he did.
And he was acting as president.
Acting as president for once or twice.
Yes, he did.
Did the students who were officers in the cadet corps enjoy any certain privileges that students who were not officers?
Oh, yes, they did.
In our own particular case, and I know in my senior year,
a couple on a couple of those theaters in Bryan.

They gave all the cadet officers a pass to those picture shows, you know, you paid the sale, or the war tax in those days was, and that was one privilege, and of course you got to wear better, you know, boots and those kind of things, and that kind of thing, and...
Were these better boots issued to you, or did you have to buy them yourself?
Uh, but I, was there a custom of all seniors wearing boots at that point?
No, not necessarily.
Now not like it's been the last few years.
We used these, that's sewn after the war, and you know in the war they wore puttees, leather puttees.
Most of them were leather puttees.
Just the regular shoes.
Yeah, with the leather puttees.
Came up here, you know, around your cap.
We have one picture, and I forget who's the man, the main man in the picture, but somebody wearing a pair of cowboy boots, and he claims those were the original Aggie boots.
They might have been back in those days.
Might have been.
What were the attitudes of the students towards the administration?
And I guess here you had a dual administrative role.
You had President Bezell on one hand and the Commandant for the Bull on the other hand.
Well, of course, the bull, the commandant, just had to charge the military affairs only.
And, well, I don't know.
We didn't have any dissension in those days.
Oh, you might fuss about them a little bit, but you heard no rabble-rousing or those kind of things about any of the teachers or professors or the bull, anybody else.
It was very cooperative.
Throughout my four years there, you didn't hear anything like that.
No.
Oh, a few little complaints, but gosh.
Nothing serious.
No strikes, no nothing like that.
Okay.
It seems to me I have a picture in the archives that's a group of students marching down to Bryan in 1919.
And somewhere I had the indication that there was some kind of a student discontent in 1919.
Was this people who had been in the service coming back and exercising some discontent or something?
The only thing I remember marching to Brown when the armistice was signed, some of the boys, I recall, marched over Brown in celebration.
But I never heard of it.
And I was there in 1919.
I don't remember any marching to Brown.
And I don't remember any protest of a group of students like that are gathering around the campus talking protest.
I never heard any of that all the time I was there.
No, sir.
The four years that you were there, do you recall that any new traditions were started?
We had some difficulty from time to time finding out when something started
I think we know about when the bonfire was first started and a few other things.
That wasn't there, no.
We had the junior banquet and that kind of thing, you know, and I presume we still do.
But I don't recall any new traditions that started while I was there, except, you know, first years there, we wore that old gray uniform.
You know, well, it wasn't long until we wore it.
begin to wear the khaki.
That was one switch from the old type uniform that was switched to the year I was there, first year I was there.
That was some tradition that was changed, of course.
Was that an improvement?

Oh yes I liked it better because well it was more casual I think and it was a trend of the times because I was there during World War I you know over the period and that was a trend of the times the khaki was accepted everywhere and the other uniform you know you'd look at well oh that's a bunch of kids or cadets or something like that you know.
Did you have a lot of trouble with those or did you have to ever have to wear those
puttees that you wrapped your leg with.
Yeah we call them wrap leggings.
Oh yes I wore them quite a bit.
They weren't bad and you know it took you a little while to learn how to wrap them but then you got away they stayed up just fine.
Yeah we wore wrap leggings we call them.
Yeah I guess the puttees are really leather.
Yeah they came up about up to here and had a buckle over here and down there.
They were leather kind of stiff leather form leather.
Was there a strap that went underneath the sole of your shoe, too?
No, I don't recall that.
No, I don't think so.
It might have been.
I don't think so.
Okay.
So, but the, uh, the leather patis, were that primarily worn by the officers?
Oh yeah, only the seniors, only the seniors.
Oh yeah, that's a special privilege.
But so all the other students have to wear the wrap leggings?
Well, yes, sir, yes they did.
And then, of course, on our hat band, you know, we had a different color hat band up here to distinguish the senior from the other classmen.
I believe the senior was gold and black.
And, uh, freshman

that was yellow blue but we had a hat band you could always tell each year each year had a different color yeah then you could tell you know it's pretty easy to tell a freshman without any coloration or anything else you know i believe now it's uh they have different colored belts oh i see i see we call them slimes in those days the fishermen slimes you know slimy fish uh-huh yeah that was your name for the fish slime slime come here slime make my bed
Slime polished my shoes.
See what I mean?
Slime, real slimy.
When a freshman encountered an upperclassman whom he had not met before, he had to introduce himself, did he refer to himself as, say, Fish Jones or Fish Allen?
I think so, yeah.
He didn't get much about fish.
They didn't call themselves slime.
Oh, no, we didn't call ourselves slime.
We called ourselves... That was...
Did you ever have any girls in any of your classes?
We know that occasionally up through the 20s there would be a girl or two in school.
There was one of the professors I recall, and I forget the professor's name now, daughter, or maybe two of them, was in class some of the years I was there.
one or two or three girls, the professor's daughters, maybe taking special courses, and they lived on the campus.
I take it all the faculty lived on the campus.
Well, some of them, I think some of them lived in Brown, maybe.
Okay, I believe.
